  <brief_title>Peristomal Mesh for Prophylaxis of Parastomal Hernia</brief_title>
  <official_title>Randomized Controlled Open Interventional Study for Evaluation of Use of Peristomal Mesh for Prophylaxis of Parastomal Hernia</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Oslo University Hospital</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Oslo University Hospital</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The study aims to prove differences or equalities in outcome for patients operated with or
      without a peristomal mesh in the sublay position when establishing a permanent colostomy.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Patients are randomized to 2 groups equal in number: a group with mesh implantation and a
      control group without mesh implantation.

      Primary endpoint is Parastomal hernia. Secondary endpoints are operating time, infection,
      obstruction, stenosis, retraction, fistulae, skin related problems and reoperations.
      Endpoints are correlated to body mass index, previous hernia, age, concurrent illness and
      cause for colostomy. Patients are followed 4 years after operation with clinical examination
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
